      "seed": 73285029,
      "version": 2359,
      "versionNonce": 1080869643,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1780673320055,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Refined knowledge: \n\n- a  shell process point toward specifc part of a ram (own virtual memory\nspace which is isolated)\n\n-  the memory a process point at ,is called, VMS(virtual memory space)\nwhich is technically accessed only by the process \n\n- we can see that memory divided in two parts (local,environment)\n\n- every variable defined without export goes in local\n\n- every variable defined with export goes to env\n\n- subprocess share the env variables of the parent process  and not the\nlocal  ones , so when a subprocess is created it point toward a VMS that\ncontains only env variables \n\n- executing a shell script open a subprocess per default , adding source\nmeans execute in current process\n\n- executing shell script without source in process A, it calls fork(), process\nB (subprocess) is a process that point to a VMS that contains the same\ncontent of VMS of process A then exec() which delete the local variable\n\n- ./script . sh = fork + exec()\nsource ./script.sh  no fork no exec()\n\n so when i run .venv/bin/activate with source path & virtual_home env\nvariable get modified , but without source , a process is created , fork() +\nexec() then modifications of env variables occurs the delete process \n\nsource,export,cd -> no fork no exec\n\nfork()  only commands create what we call  subshells\ncan be defined using parentheses : (val='x',echo$x)\n| fork alsso\n\nstandard utilities (ls,grep,cat,..) + scripts (py,sh,js) + compilers = (fork()\n+exec())\n\n\nif i  defined x=5 and export x=10 , when trying to access x  using $x i\nwould access the env one or local one ? in local first then it get\noverwritted by 10 and become env \n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n",
      "fontSize": 19.999999999999993,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Refined knowledge: \n\n- a  shell process point toward specifc part of a ram (own virtual memory space which is isolated)\n\n-  the memory a process point at ,is called, VMS(virtual memory space) which is technically accessed only by the process \n\n- we can see that memory divided in two parts (local,environment)\n\n- every variable defined without export goes in local\n\n- every variable defined with export goes to env\n\n- subprocess share the env variables of the parent process  and not the local  ones , so when a subprocess is created it point toward a VMS that contains only env variables \n\n- executing a shell script open a subprocess per default , adding source means execute in current process\n\n- executing shell script without source in process A, it calls fork(), process B (subprocess) is a process that point to a VMS that contains the same content of VMS of process A then exec() which delete the local variable\n\n- ./script . sh = fork + exec()\nsource ./script.sh  no fork no exec()\n\n so when i run .venv/bin/activate with source path & virtual_home env variable get modified , but without source , a process is created , fork() + exec() then modifications of env variables occurs the delete process \n\nsource,export,cd -> no fork no exec\n\nfork()  only commands create what we call  subshells\ncan be defined using parentheses : (val='x',echo$x)\n| fork alsso\n\nstandard utilities (ls,grep,cat,..) + scripts (py,sh,js) + compilers = (fork() +exec())\n\n\nif i  defined x=5 and export x=10 , when trying to access x  using $x i would access the env one or local one ? in local first then it get overwritted by 10 and become env \n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n",
      "autoResize": false,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    }
